<HEADLINE> Russian Forces Launch Preemptive Strike in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Russian forces launched a preemptive
strike early Monday against some 150-200 militants inside its
breakaway Chechen republic, killing a number of rebels, Interior
Minister Vladimir Rushailo said.
</P>
<P>
The operation was taken at around 06:00 and involved helicopter
gunships and mortars, Rushailo said following a meeting with
President Boris Yeltsin, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The militants sustained casualties. We know from intercepts of
radio messages that a number of militants were killed," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue doing our best to prevent cross-border
attacks from Chechnya on our checkpoints and civilians," he said.
</P>
<P>
The move came after Rushailo's announcement last Saturday that
orders had been given to deliver "preventive strikes on places of
concentration of guerrillas and hardware discovered through
intelligence activities."
</P>
<P>
He characterized the strikes as "a local operation to respond
to the attacks on our checkpoints and roadblocks" rather than
"strategic strikes on the Chechen territory," Rushailo said in an
interview with the RTR television Vesti program.
</P>
<P>
Russia dispatched a temporary group of 17,000 troops in the
North Caucasus region, with 10,000 of them constantly deployed on
the Chechen border.
</P>
<P>
There have been frequent attacks on checkpoints and civilians
in the areas along the administrative border with Chechnya in the
past few months. A number of bomb explosions in Moscow, notably
inside the reception center of the Federal Security Service and
the lobby of the Interior Ministry, were also believed to be
connected to the Chechen militants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
