<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian President Arrives in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafiz al-Assad
arrived here Monday for a two-day official visit to Russia seen as
a landmark in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Assad, here on his first official visit to post-Soviet Russia,
was received at the airport by Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian president, leading a delegation that includes
foreign, defense and economics ministers, is scheduled to meet
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Stepashin on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Very serious negotiations are planned on the most important
strategic issues, both on the situation in the Middle East and on
the bilateral relations," said Sergei Prikhodko, Yeltsin's deputy
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
"Syria plays a key role (in the Middle East) and Russia is a
co-sponsor (of the Mideast peace process). So it largely depends
on their interaction how stable peace in that region will be," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also discuss economic issues, Prikhodko
said.
</P>
<P>
"For a number of years, right until last year, economic
relations between our countries were unfortunately in a state of
stagnation," Prikhodko said.
</P>
<P>
"It was only recently that a tendency for an increase became
evident. Undoubtedly, both presidents will make every effort to
sustain this increase," he said.
</P>
<P>
Assad last visited Moscow in 1990, when Russia was still part
of the Soviet Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
