<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activists Meet to Push Forward Mideast Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of peace activists gathered
here Monday to call for momentum to the Middle East peace process,
which has increased hope of breakthrough now that Israel is about
to change the government.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the peace meeting included Egyptians,
Israelis, Jordanians and Palestinians. They met to seek ways of
promoting closer ties between Arab countries and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Moderate Ehud Barak, leader of the Israeli Labor Party,
trounced hardline incumbent Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in the May 17 elections. Barak, pledging to advance the
Arab-Israeli peace talks, will assume power this week.
</P>
<P>
The peace meeting was organized by the International Alliance
for Arab-Israeli Peace that was set up in Denmark in 1997 by
Middle East lawmakers, religious leaders and intellectuals. The
group is also known as the Copenhagen group.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian former Prime Minister Mustafa Khalil, who chaired the
meeting, conveyed President Hosni Mubarak's greetings and wishes
of success to the conference for peace.
</P>
<P>
Khalil reviewed the peace-making between Egypt and Israel,
which resulted in the signing of the first peace treaty in 1979
between an Arab country and the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"We celebrated the 20th anniversary of the signing of the peace
treaty, and our responsibility is to defend peace," he told the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Peace between Egypt and Israel had been for long seen as
impossible but we have overcome all obstacles and eventually
achieved peace," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, before the peace meeting opened in the evening,
hundreds of Egyptian politicians, artists and writers gathered
earlier in the day to protest the conference.
</P>
<P>
The protesters met inside a hall to hear speeches condemning
Egypt's 1979 peace treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the peace treaty say Arabs should have no
relations with the Jewish state until it withdraws from all
territories it occupied after the 1967 Mideast war, including east
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
