<HEADLINE> Sharif Leaves Washington for New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Prime minister Nawaz
Sharif left Washington on Monday for New York after his Sunday
meeting with President Bill Clinton over Kashmir conflict, a
Pakistan embassy official said.
</P>
<P>
He will be meeting with leaders of the Pakistan community in
the United States behind closed doors before leaving New York late
in the day, the official said. He will not meet any U.N. officials
there, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif and Clinton issued a joint statement after their meeting
at the Blair House in Washington. The statement said "concrete
steps" would be taken to restore the Line of Control in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The agreement sought to defuse a six-week conflict that has
pitted Indian armed forces against the guerrillas and has been
described as the worst crisis between the two South Asian rivals
in nearly 30 years. 
</P>
