<HEADLINE> Mini-summit to Be Held on S. Leone Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Four west African presidents are
scheduled to hold a one-day meeting Tuesday with key officials of
the rebels in Sierra Leone in a bid to resolve "sticking points"
in the draft pact to end the eight-year crisis in that country.
</P>
<P>
A top official of the Nigerian Ministry of Foreign Affairs said
here Monday that Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo and his
counterparts Charles Taylor of Liberia, Tejan Kabbah of Sierra
leone and Gnassingbe Eyadema of Togo would attend the talks in
Togolese capital Lome tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The unidentified official pointed out that "we are working on
bringing key officials of the rebel group, including its military
leader, Sam Bockarie to the talks."
</P>
<P>
The talks are coming two days after "rank and file members" of
the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) reportedly rejected as
"not enough" the four cabinet posts offered in the draft
agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The People's War Council has told me that it is not enough,"
leader of the rebel RUF Foday Sankoh reportedly said, referring to
the four positions offered to the rebels in a national unity
government.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, who has been involved in six weeks of talks in the
Togolese capital, said that the council insists on the seven posts
as well as the position of the vice-president in the government of
national unity.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministry official was, however, optimistic about
the prospects of Tuesday's mini-summit in resolving the
outstanding issues of the peace talks hosted by President Eyadema,
current chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
He noted that "we want to make sure all the key officials
attend the meeting, particularly those in the bush, to ensure we
extract an agreement from them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
