<HEADLINE> Ministers Put Final Touches to Draft Cease-Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Ministers attending the peace talks
for ending the 11-month conflict in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) in Zambian capital Lusaka put final touches Monday to
a long-awaited draft cease-fire document.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Presidential Affairs Minister Eric Silwamba told
reporters that a sub-committee set up by the ministers had worked
overnight to finish papers which set out the cease-fire terms.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba said the sub-committee worked late into the early
hours of Monday morning to finish all documents to be adopted by
the ministers at a plenary session later.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the draft pact would be followed by a heads of
state signing ceremony with the date to be announced soon, said
the minister.
</P>
<P>
The regional summit in Lusaka, which had dragged on for 11
days, was aimed at ending almost a year of fighting between rebels
and Congolese government forces.
</P>
<P>
Three Congolese rebel groups and a government delegation led by
 Congolese Foreign Minister Abdoulaye Yerodia Ndombasi have agreed
that a new national army would be created out of the rebel forces
and the government army.
</P>
<P>
The government and the rebels also appear to agree in principle
on the withdrawal of foreign troops from the vast central African
country.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba said the problem of obtaining documents in both
English and French had delayed the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The foreign countries involved in the conflict -- rebel allies
Rwanda and Uganda, and the government backers Namibia, Angola and
Zimbabwe also appear to have resolved their main differences.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting started last Monday, attended by
defense, home and foreign affairs ministers from the 14 Southern
African Development Community (SADC) member states, as well as
Rwanda, Uganda and Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
