<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sultan's Visit to Consolidate UAE-Saudi Ties: UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) said Monday that the visit of Saudi Prince
Sultan Ibn Abdul Aziz to the country Tuesday will consolidate the
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The visit of Prince Sultan, who is also Saudi second deputy
premier and minister of defense and aviation, "will have a
positive impact on the consolidation of bilateral relations and we
are confident that it will add a new value to these ties," said
UAE Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Sheikh Hamdan Bin Zayed
Al Nahyan.
</P>
<P>
Hamdan told the official WAM news agency that Prince Sultan's
visit "is taking place within the framework of bilateral contacts
between the UAE-Saudi leaderships to discuss the latest
developments and ways of preserving security and stability in the
strategic Gulf region."
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the UAE's appreciation of the support from
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states for the UAE's
sovereignty over three disputed islands with Iran, WAM said.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, foreign ministers of the GCC, which groups Saudi
Arabia, the UAE, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain, issued a joint
statement following a one-day meeting. They expressed support for
the UAE's sovereignty over the islands of Abu Musa and Greater and
Lesser Tunbs.
</P>
<P>
They also set up a tripartite committee with members from
Saudi Arabia, Oman and Qatar to work out a mechanism for direct
negotiations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was the continuation of the 71th session of the GCC
Ministerial Council. The session was suspended in June because of
a row between the UAE and Saudi Arabia over the latter's efforts
to improve ties with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has always required its GCC allies to help solve the
islands dispute first before warming up relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The row was difused later following the mediation efforts
by Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al Thani. 
</P>
</TEXT>
