<HEADLINE> S. African Car Sales Down in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It said the decline of 15.6 percent -- 15,588 units down from
last year' s 18,474 units -- was a continuation of the difficult
and recessionary business conditions in the South African
automotive industry over the past two and three quarter years.
</P>
<P>
However Naamsa anticipated that the long-awaited turnaround in
the automotive industry would start in the third quarter of the
year, together with signs of some improvement in activity at
retail level.
</P>
<P>
Last month's sales also showed a "modest decline" of 327 units,
or two percent, compared with May.
</P>
<P>
"Sales of new light commercial vehicles, bakkies (light
delivery vehicles) and mini-buses at 7,965 units for June 1999
reflected a decline of 533 units or 6.3 percent compared to the
8,489 unit sales recorded during June 1998," Naamsa said.
</P>
<P>
"Compared to May 1999 - the latest month's sales of light
commercial vehicles had remained fully unchanged, recording a
slight fall of 11 units or 0.1 percent."
</P>
<P>
Naamsa also said medium and heavy truck sales also recorded
sharp declines last month and at 398 units and 425 units
respectively, reflected falls of 126 units or 24.1 percent,
compared to the sales levels of the corresponding month last year.
</P>
<P>
"However, both sectors had managed modest improvements compared
to the previous month's sales, rising by 12.4 percent (medium
commercials) and 1.0 percent (heavy trucks and busses)."
</P>
<P>
Vehicle sales were also sharply down in the last six months,
compared with the first half of last year - with new car sale
registering a fall of 18.4 percent, light commercial vehicles down
by 9.5 percent, medium commercial vehicles falling by 19.9 percent
and heavy trucks and busses by 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the significant and welcome reduction in interest
rates, private consumption expenditure in South Africa remained
under pressure and South African consumers generally appeared
reluctant to spend and incur additional debt.
</P>
<P>
"Investment trends, too, remained under pressure. However,
South Africa' s economic fundamentals were becoming progressively
more positive and conducive to further interest rate reductions
and a recovery in general economic activity levels during the
second half of the year."
</P>
<P>
"Despite an expected modest recovery during the second half of
1999, for the year as a whole the industry continued to anticipate
lower overall new vehicle sales compared to 1998."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Toyota announced Monday that the month just passed
was a " bumper month" in which it took 27.9 percent of the market
share, selling mostly Conquests, Hiluxes and Corollas.
</P>
<P>
"The month saw sales of individual model ranges move above
2,000 units for the first time in many months with Toyota selling
2,356 Conquests and 2, 142 Hilux commercial vehicles. Corolla
sales boosted Toyota's figures by a further 1,276 units." 
</P>
