<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President on SAARC Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga said here Monday evening that much more must be done
to make the potential of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) tangible to the peoples of the region.
</P>
<P>
In her speech at a state banquet hosted in her honor by Nepali
King Birendra, Kumaratunga, who is also the current SAARC
chairman, noted that the member states have been able to follow up
systematically on the decisions taken at the 10th SAARC Summit
held in Colombo, Sri Lanka, in July last year.
</P>
<P>
"The process of our collective preparation for the forthcoming
WTO (World Trade Organization) ministerial round, which is almost
a synonym for globalization, is well under way," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We have made good progress in our contacts with the European
Union as well," she said. "We are poised to achieve a similar
positive outcome in our relationship with ASEAN (the Association
of South-East Asian Nations)."
</P>
<P>
She said the SAARC, which groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka, has made some progress in
some other areas of mutual cooperation agreed upon at the Colombo
summit such as setting up a network for economic research and
working together on distance education.
</P>
<P>
"Much more, however, requires to be done to make the potential
of SAARC tangible to the peoples of South Asia," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
She noted that some of the technical cooperation activities
under the Integrated Program of Action have become desultory. She
called for greater purposefulness and vigor to be directed toward
this important area of the SAARC.
</P>
<P>
She also stressed steady progress in SAARC efforts on the SAARC
Preferential Trading Arrangement (SAPTA) and its later stage of
South Asian Free Trade Area (SAFTA).
</P>
<P>
She held that the respect and attention which the SAARC
receives from the outside world would be determined by the
strength and vitality of the SAARC's own regional programs.
</P>
<P>
SAARC leaders had preferred to set up the SAFTA by 2001 but
deferred it indefinitely at the Colombo summit.
</P>
<P>
The fourth round of trade negotiations under the SAPTA is
scheduled to start this month.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga arrived here Monday afternoon on a four-day state
visit. She is scheduled to visit the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Secretariat during her stay here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
