<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Prime Minister-Elect Finalizes Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud
Barak officially wrapped up six-week-plus coalition talks Monday
and will present his cabinet list to the Knesset (parliament) for
approval Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The incoming seven-faction coalition comprises One Israel, the
ultra-Orthodox Shas Party, the United Torah Judaism, Meretz, the
Center Party, the Russian immigrants party Yisrael b'Aliya and
National Religious Party.
</P>
<P>
One Israel, consisting of the Labor Party, Gesher and the
moderate religious movement Meimad, is the biggest party in the
Knesset with 26 seats, which is followed by Shas with 17 seats.
</P>
<P>
Among the cabinet ministers he appointed Monday, Abraham
Shohat will be finance minister, Yossi Beilin justice minister
and Shlomo Ben-Ami public security minister.
</P>
<P>
Labor legislator Dalia Itzik will be the only one woman
minister in Barak's cabinet. She will head the Environment
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Former Prime Minister Shimon Peres will head a new ministry of
regional development, which will focus on economic cooperation
between Israel and its Arab neighbors. But he is at odds with
Barak over the responsibility of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Israeli markets reacted nervously to the news that Shohat,
finance minister in the former Labor government in 1992-1996
with a bad reputation for overspending and loose financial
policy, will return to the post.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Tel Aviv-100 index was down 1.49 percent to
close at 421.02 points and Israeli shekel declined to 4.097
against the dollar from Friday's 4.075.
</P>
<P>
But some experts said it is unclear whether Shohat will repeat
his financial policy, which caused the budget and the current
account deficits to swell to dangerous levels, since Barak's
platform on economy has been drawn on very vague terms.
</P>
<P>
In an internal defiance to Barak who is regarded by many of his
colleagues as being left with too much power, the Labor central
committee rejected Barak's hand-picked candidate for the Knesset
speaker.
</P>
<P>
In a secret ballot, the central committee chose Avraham Burg,
No. 7 in the One Israel Knesset list, instead of Barak's choice,
Shalom Simhon, who has served only one term in the Knesset, as One
Israel's candidate for Knesset speaker.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset will elect a new speaker soon before it casts a
confidence vote on the new government Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
