<HEADLINE> Croatia Ready to Boost Cooperation With Egypt: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic
said here on Monday that his country is ready to enhance economic
cooperation with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with his Egyptian
counterpart Amr Moussa, Granic described the talks as "fruitful
and constructive," Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Croatia and Egypt are planning to sign an
agreement on preventing dual taxation, highlighting the close
cooperation between the two countries in various domains.
</P>
<P>
Granic arrived here on Sunday for a three-day visit. He is
scheduled to meet with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on
Tuesday, during which he is to convey a message to Mubarak from
Croatian President Franjo Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said their discussions dealt with the political
developments of the situation in the Middle East, the Balkan
region and the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
Noting that a group of businessmen are accompanying the
Croatian foreign minister, Moussa played up chances for promoting
the bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Egypt and Croatia "are required to exert bulky
efforts to redress the deficiency in" the trade volume, which
stands at about 40 million U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the talks, the two sides signed three agreements
covering cultural cooperation, consultations between the two
countries' foreign ministries and revocation of visas for holders
of diplomatic passports.
</P>
<P>
Also Monday, Granic met with Egyptian Minister of Economy
Yousef Boutros Ghali to review prospects of furthering bilateral
economic cooperation, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to set up a governmental mechanism to
oversee ways of promoting cooperation and to coordinate efforts
exerted by the two countries' businessmen in bolstering
investments.
</P>
<P>
During his ongoing visit, the Croatian official is also
expected to meet with Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid to seek ways of enhancing relations between Croatia
and the Arab world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
