<HEADLINE> Indian Diplomat Reported Abducted in Islamabad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indian High Commission in
Islamabad Monday accused Pakistan of abducting its diplomat for
the second time in a week.
</P>
<P>
The high commission said in a press release that one of its
staff members, Yog Raj Vij, was abducted in a pre-planned manner
by Pakistani intelligence operatives on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Yog Raj Vij was kidnapped just outside his house on his return
from office and taken away in a vehicle to an unknown location,
said the press release.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, another commission staff member, T. R. Nair
was attacked and beaten up with sticks and received "injuries all
over his body," said the press release.
</P>
<P>
This abduction is "a serious and unacceptable incident" and "a
blatant violation of established norms," said the press release.
</P>
<P>
The Indian High Commission has lodged a strong protest with the
Pakistani Foreign Office, urging the Pakistani government to take
urgent steps for the "immediate and safe" return of Yog Raj Vij.
</P>
<P>
Zameer Akram, spokesman for the Pakistan Foreign Office, said
they have received this protest note from the Indian High
Commission and are "investigating into the accusation whether
that person has been abducted or not."
</P>
<P>
"After the investigation, we will be to reply to this
allegation," said Akram.
</P>
<P>
The Indian High Commission accused the Pakistani government of
abducting one of its staff members, N. R. Doraiswamy, on June 29,
but Pakistan rejected the accusation.
</P>
<P>
Prior to that, Pakistan had said India abducted one of the
staff members of the Pakistani High Commission in New Delhi on
June 28, whom India then expelled on charges of spying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
