<HEADLINE> SADC Says Cereal Deficit "No Cause for Alarm" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The incessant rains of the 1989/99 agricultural season and the
 following dry spell have led to the prospects of reduced crop
production," South African Press Association quoted SADC as saying
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"An all cereals deficit of two million tons is now estimated as
of May.
</P>
<P>
"This is no cause for alarm, since it includes nominal
strategic reserve requirements. Some countries will, however, have
to import maize and wheat."
</P>
<P>
The committee of SADC's ministers for food, agriculture and
natural resources, met at SADC headquarters in Gaborone on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers announced "The Hub" -- an initiative to
facilitate regional cooperation to improve food security and rural
development, including trade in agricultural products, improved
cooperation with the European Union (EU), and moves to combat
heart water disease and control tick infestations.
</P>
<P>
"'The Hub', would be the missing link between the SADC regional
and national food security programs," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Officially titled the "SADC Food Security and Rural Development
Hub", it would be backed by a Regional Program for Communication
for Development and an Agricultural Potential Information System.
</P>
<P>
"The Hub will facilitate the implementation of food security
and rural development programs in SADC member states through
capacity building and resource mobilization at both local and
regional levels," the ministers said.
</P>
<P>
"The communication program will be aimed at making sure the
intended beneficiaries of rural development programs can
participate in decision- making affecting their lives."
</P>
<P>
A donors conference to start the implementation of the Hub is
to be convened for July 23 in Harare, Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are under way to improve international cooperation in
agriculture between SADC, other regional bodies and, particularly,
the EU.
</P>
<P>
SADC and EU agriculture ministers have agreed to engage in
regular specialist dialog, involving not only their governments,
but also farmers unions and "non-state actors".
</P>
<P>
The 14 member states of SADC are: Angola, Botswana, Democratic
Republic of Congo, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique,
Namibia, Seychelles, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
