<HEADLINE> Iraq May Exceed Oil Export Quota: U.N. Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraq will earn more revenues than
the quota set by the U.N. Security Council for the sixth phase of
the oil-for-food program if the current high oil prices continue,
said a senior U.N. official here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Benon Sevan, executive director of the U.N. Program for Iraq,
made the remarks at a press conference held here.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the oil prices on the world markets can
maintain the current going-up trend or based on last Friday's 14.5
dollars per barrel, Iraq's receipts from selling oil exceed the
5.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. oil-for-food program started in 1996 for
under-sanction Iraq to export limited amount of oil every six
months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for
its nearly 24 million people.
</P>
<P>
The ceiling for oil exports has been raised from 2.8 billion
dollars to 5.2 billion since the fourth phase of the program.
</P>
<P>
Sevan admitted that "no matter what we do... there is no way we
can meet all the needs of the Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long complained that this humanitarian program has
done little to achieve that goal.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has been pressing for the total lifting of the nearly
nine-year-old U.N. sanctions imposed on the country following its
1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Sevan, who arrived here on June 16 and will leave Tuesday, said
that after war compensation and other deductions from the Iraqi
oil proceeds, Iraq will get 3.4 billion dollars for humanitarian
purposes.
</P>
<P>
Low oil prices on the world market and the severe lack of spare
parts for its oil sector have enable Iraq to export only some 3
billion dollars and 3.9 billion dollars in the fourth and fifth
phase respectively.
</P>
<P>
Under the current sixth phase, which started on May 25, Iraq's
oil exports have been running at 2.2 million barrel per day.
</P>
<P>
It will be up to the Security Council to decide whether Iraq
will be allowed to exceed the oil export ceiling of 5.2 billion
dollars before the end of this phase, said Seven, the
highest-ranking U.N. official in charge of the Iraqi humanitarian
program.
</P>
<P>
During his 20-day visit to Iraq, Sevan toured some areas in the
country, including the northern Kurdish autonomous regions, and
held talks with Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadhan and
Iraqi ministers concerned.
</P>
<P>
"I am very happy with the results achieved during my visit,"
he told the press conference. But he did not elaborate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
