<HEADLINE> 1 Killed, 10 Injured in Landmine Explosions in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- One person was killed and 10 others
injured in two landmine explosions in southeastern Turkey on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
A landmine, planted by militants of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), exploded Monday when a minibus pressed it
near Uzumlu village in Durankaya town of Hakkari province,
leaving one person dead and five others, including three village
guards, injured.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a vehicle belonging to the Turkish
Petroleum Corporation hit a landmine also planted by the PKK
rebels in Batman province Sunday night, injuring five, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
One person was killed and 14 others wounded in a suicide
bombing in Adana, southern Turkey, Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Late Sunday night, one person was killed and 25 others injured
when a time bomb exploded in a dustbin in a picnic place at
Avcilar district of Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Istanbul Governor Erol Cakir accused the PKK of being
responsible for the explosions.
</P>
<P>
The attacks were suspected of retaliation acts launched by PKK
rebels because their leader Abdullah Ocalan was sentenced to
death last Tuesday on charges of treason and separatism.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan-led PKK has been fighting a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Conflicts between the
Turkish security forces and the PKK militants have claimed over
37,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was captured by Turkish special agents in Kenya in
mid-February and has ever since been detained on Imrali Island
in Marmara Sea near western Turkey's province of Bursa where
he was tried on charges of treasons and separatism.
</P>
</TEXT>
