<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Guerrilla Killed in Israeli Air Raid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's anti-occupation Muslim
group Hezbollah, or Party of God, Monday announced that one of its
fighters died in Israeli air raids on Lebanon last month.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the group said that Abas Mohmmed
Toufeili died of injury he sustained during the Israeli air raid
on the country's eastern Baalbek late June 24.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Israel launched heavy attacks on Lebanon's
infrastructure and the group's suspected bases in Baalbek,
killing eight people and wounding 64.
</P>
<P>
Two power stations, three bridges and a telephone relay station
around Beirut were also destroyed in the blitz which was seen as
the heaviest since the Israeli 16-day "Grapes of Wrath" operation
on Lebanon in April 1996. More than 200 people, most of them
civilians, were killed in the operation.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed that its offensives on Lebanon were aimed at
retaliating Hezbollah's cross-border attacks while Hezbollah
argued it fired Katyusha rockets into northern Israel to avenge
the wounding of six Lebanese civilians by Israeli shelling in
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The latest attack raised to 15 the number of Hezbollah
guerrillas killed in south Lebanon since the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
Ten Israeli soldiers were killed in the border zone during the
same period.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli forces and its proxy
South Lebanon Army out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
