<HEADLINE> Rios Rusty after Five-week Injury Layoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Chilian Marcelo Rios showed sign of
rust from a five-week injury layoff as the former world number one
sweated to a three-set clay win at the Swiss Open at Gstaad on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rios wrapped up a 6-2, 6-7 (7/9), 7-6 (7/1) victory over Czech
Bohdan Ulihrach to advance to the second round of the 550,000 U.S.
dollars tournament.
</P>
<P>
Rios, seeded third, has not played since losing in the quarter-
finals of the French Open to Dominic Hrbaty. He cited lower back
pain before pulling out of the Wimbledon Championships a fortnight
ago.
</P>
<P>
Another seed who is also coming off a long break is Spanish
titleholder Alex Corretja who opens with a first round match on
Tuesday against Nicolas Lapentti.
</P>
<P>
Top seed is Brazil's Gustavo Kuerten, who will face off against
fellow South American Mariano Puerta of Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Briton Greg Rusedski will be tuning up his huge serve to take
on another heavy hitter Swiss Marc Rosset.
</P>
<P>
On a low-key opening day, there was disappointment for Swiss
Lorenzo Manta, who was dismissed 6-1, 6-1 by eighth seed Albert
Costa of Spain, the 1996 champion.
</P>
<P>
Manta, ranked world No. 112, had surprised on the grass at
Wimbledon by reaching the fourth round before losing to Kuerten.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere two qualifiers moved ahead. Croatian Ivan Ljubicic
downed Czech Daniel Vacek 6-7 (5/7) 6-4, 6-4 and Italy's Andrea
Gaudenzi had an easy time against Rainer Schuttler, knocking out
the only German in the 32-man field 6-2, 6-1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
