<HEADLINE> Tri-Lateral Protocol on Regional Project Signed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A tri-lateral protocol aimed
at stimulating investment, agriculture and tourism in the region
straddling South Africa, Swaziland and Mozambique was signed at
the Southern African Economic Summit in Durban Monday.
</P>
<P>
The protocol for the one-billion rand (167-million-U.S.
dollars) Lubombo Spatial Development Initiative was signed by
South African President Thabo Mbeki, Swaziland's King Mswati III
and President Joaquim Chissano of Mozambique, according to South
African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said the protocol was designed to foster private
sector confidence and help attract as much investment as possible
in the region, which includes parts of eastern Swaziland, southern
Mozambique and northern KwaZulu-Natal of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to them, the protocol laid down the legal framework
for the initiative and would serve as forerunner to other
protocols on such diverse aspects as malaria control, cross-border
movements and conservation.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said the signing of the protocol was a practical
expression of a theme that has run through the economy: namely
Mbeki's emphasis on regional cooperation and collaboration as a
way to stimulate industrial revival and job creation on the
sub-continent.
</P>
<P>
A lighter moment during the signing revealed that even state
leaders are often nervous around royalty when Mbeki quipped that
he had mistakenly signed where the Swazi king should have signed.
</P>
</TEXT>
