<HEADLINE> Dutch GDP Growth To Slowdown In 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands Bureau for
Economic Policy Analysis said in The Hague on Monday that it
expects growth of Gross Domestic products (GDP) in the country to
slowdown this year to 2.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau said the GDP growth forecast for the year of 2000 is
two percent, this marked slowdown in relation to the 3.8 percent
of growth in 1998 is due in particular to the slower growth of
exports.
</P>
<P>
However, the expected rate of growth is somewhat higher than
the forecast three months ago, it said. Because of the strong U.S.
dollar, the competitive position is more favorable and the
decreasing growth in exports need not be as pronounced as
anticipated previously, it added.
</P>
<P>
The government policy research body also said that consumsption
is continuing to grow strongly this year to about 3.75 percent,
although the growth next year will slow to 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"By contrast exports will pick up vigorously, in particular
from the third quarter of 1999 onwards. This will mean export
growth for 1999 as a whole of 2.5 percent," the bureau said,
adding it expects an increase in exports of 5.25 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The government bureau also was optimistic on the overall
economic picture. "The slower economic growth will still result in
a two percent rise in employment this year, or 135,000 jobs.
Unemployment will fall further to 4.5 percent as in 1998, and
inflation this year will probably amount to two percent, while
next year it is expected to fall to 1.5 percent". 
</P>
</TEXT>
