<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Vows Not to Withdraw From LoC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A Pakistan military spokesman
Monday said there is no question of a Pakistan withdrawal from its
side of the Line of Control (LoC) in the disputed region of
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Brigadier Rashid Qureshi, director general of the
Inter-Services Public Relations, at a press briefing declined to
comment on Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's meeting with U.S.
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
But he said there is no question of withdrawal from Pakistan's
side of the LoC.
</P>
<P>
"How could we withdraw from the LoC?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that Pakistan troops have not crossed the LoC.
"Pakistan Army is on the Line of Control, I repeat, Pakistan Army
is on the Line of Control," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif rushed to Washington late Saturday night and held a
three-hour meeting with Clinton, after which the two leaders
issued a joint statement calling on both Pakistan and India to
respect the LoC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
