<DOCNO> XIE19990706.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Urges India, Pakistan to Resolve Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Kumaratunga on Monday urged India and Pakistan to sit
down in a sincere endeavor to remove the irritants and resolve the
problems that have so long bedeviled their relationship.
</P>
<P>
In her speech at a state banquet hosted in her honor by Nepali
King Birendra, Kumaratunga said, "We are committed to the pursuit
of regional cooperation," but conflict and discord between
countries in any part of the region affect every part of the
region.
</P>
<P>
At the ninth summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) in May 1997 in the Maldives, she noted,
leaders of the member states including India and Pakistan
recognized that peace, stability, amity and accelerated social and
economic cooperation may best be achieved by fostering
good-neighborly relations, relieving tensions and building
confidence.
</P>
<P>
SAARC was formed in December 1985 to promote social and
economic development in the region through cooperation among its
seven member states -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. Kumaratunga is the current chairman
of the regional grouping.
</P>
<P>
"The leaders of both India and Pakistan are statesmen with a
shared vision of peace and progress, not only for their respective
nations, but also for the region of South Asia," she said.
</P>
<P>
The president cautioned that tension and conflict between India
and Pakistan sap their energy, drain their resources, impede their
economic development and postpone the day when all the peoples in
the region can share the fruits of peace and tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, King Birendra also called for an environment
of mutual trust and working together in making the SAARC region
even more effective in the international arena through exchange of
experiences and proper utilization of human and natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga arrived here Monday afternoon for a four-day state
visit at the invitation of Birendra. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
