<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Irish Protestant Leader Calls Blair "Unconvincing" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Senior Northern Ireland Protestant
politician Ken Maginnis said Monday that British Prime Minister
Tony Blair's latest peace plan for the province was unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
Maginnis, security spokesman for the British province's main
Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, told Channel Four
television that what was needed was a clear commitment from the
Irish Republican Army on disarmament.
</P>
<P>
"As always, Tony Blair's arguments are compelling but they're
not convincing," Maginnis said, accusing the IRA's political wing
Sinn Fein of not having given straight answers on the
make-or-break disarmament issue.
</P>
<P>
If the IRA said it was going to enter into "serious
negotiations with John de Chastelain of the disarmament commission
and are going to achieve disarmament by the 22nd of May next year,
then I believe there would be an onus, and only then, on my party
to change its policy," Maginnis said.
</P>
<P>
Blair, seeking Protestant support for his latest peace
blueprint for Northern Ireland, earlier Monday accepted a key
demand of Ulster Unionists worried about entering government with
Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
He told parliament that Sinn Fein would have to quit the
province's planned all-party executive immediately if the IRA
failed to start disarming on schedule, and he would encourage
other parties to govern without them, according to a Reuters
report.
</P>
<P>
The disarmament wrangle has paralyzed the Northern Ireland
peace process and thrown into jeopardy last year's Good Friday
accord for the future of the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
