<HEADLINE> Russian Satellite Launch Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The mission control center lost
contact with a Russian military communications satellite launched
earlier Monday, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Raduga satellite was not responding to signals from the
center and was not transmitting any information to the ground.
Some experts said the satellite might have dropped to the ground
in Russia's Altai area.
</P>
<P>
Raduga blasted off from the Baikonur cosmodrome in Kazakhstan
at 17:32 Moscow time (1332 GMT), and all three stages of the
Proton-K carrier performed well.
</P>
<P>
However, about 10 minutes after takeoff, when Raduga and the
new Briz-M booster were in a preliminary orbit, the satellite
stopped reacting to commands from the ground and failed to send
information. Spotting devices also stopped tracing it.
</P>
<P>
The launch of Raduga had been postponed several times due to a
unit replacement and extra tests of the Briz-M, which had not been
used in space flight before.
</P>
<P>
Malfunctions in fueling pumps were attributed to the latest
postponement, from Sunday to Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
