<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Late Zimbabwean VP Buried In Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 50,000 Zimbabweans from all over the country gathered at
the Acre to bid farewell to veteran nationalist fighter Nkomo.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time since the national shrine was built in
the early 1980s that those numbers flocked to the national shrine.
</P>
<P>
Before Nkomo was taken to rest in full military honors to a 19
gun- salute by a 25 pounder cannon as in accordance with his post,
three speakers told of the gallant's exploits of the
vice-president of the country.
</P>
<P>
In an almost two-hour eulogy, President Robert Mugabe highly
praised Nkomo's outstanding contributions to the country's
struggle for independence, national unity and stability, and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said one could not help appreciate and admire the
vice-president's commitment to national unity.
</P>
<P>
He urged Zimbabweans not to be swayed by those who wanted to
divide the country, saying that Zimbabweans should emulate Nkomo's
ideologies and principles.
</P>
<P>
"There are other external forces who say that unity of
political parties is a non-democratic process," Mugabe said.
"Unity is essential if we are to maintain a peaceful environment.
Unity, unity -- Mugabe has pledged unity of the people."
</P>
<P>
On December 22 ,1987, Nkomo and Mugabe signed the historic
Unity Accord between the Zimbabwe African People's Union (ZAPU)
led by Nkomo and the Zimbabwe African National Union (ZANU) led by
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Nkomo was born on June 7, 1917 in Matabeleland Province in
west Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
In 1951, he was elected secretary of the Railway African
Workers' Union. In 1952, he was elected President of the African
national Congress.
</P>
<P>
On August 8, 1990, Nkomo was sworn in as Co-Vice-President of
Zimbabwe, together with Simon Muzenda -- a post he held till his
death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
