<HEADLINE> FM: Belarus Views Russia as Main Strategic Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian Foreign Minister Ural
Latypov said Monday that despite President Alexander Lukashenko's
criticism of Moscow's slow action in the union of the two
countries, Russia remains Minsk's main strategic partner.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to Lukashenko's warning last Friday that if
Russia takes no concrete, real steps toward integration with
Belarus, Minsk would reconsider its foreign policy doctrine by
giving priority to cooperation with the West.
</P>
<P>
That statement "does not mean that Minsk has changed its policy
in relation to Russia," the Interfax news agency quoted Latypov as
saying in Minsk.
</P>
<P>
"Russia remains our main strategic partner," and Belarus favors
"the exhaustive and timely implementation of the agreements
reached within the framework of the Belarussian- Russian Union,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Lukashenko's "determination to normalize
relations with the West cannot be viewed as an alternative to
cooperation with Russia."
</P>
<P>
"Belarus will survive only if it maintains normal relations
with both East and West," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The normalization of relations with the European Union is not
empty rhetoric, calculated for a momentary effect, but a long-term
aspect of Belarussian foreign policy," Latypov said.
</P>
<P>
"We think we can simultaneously maintain good relations with
the West and with Russia," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
