<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Peace in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Monday called on all parties to the Northern Ireland conflict to
work hard for a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
Jake Siewert, a White House spokesman, said that Clinton had a
brief telephone talk with Northern Ireland's leading Unionist
politician David Trimble about the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The conversation took place while the president was en route to
Kentucky on a bid to expand economic opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was urging those involved "to continue their hard work
at resolving the conflicts," Siewert said.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Ireland put forward the proposals last week in a
bid to break the deadlock over guerrilla disarmament which has
jeopardized the Good Friday peace accord of April 1998.
</P>
<P>
Protestant politicians, who back British rule, have accused
British Prime Minister Tony Blair of making too many concessions
to the Catholics, who want to link up with Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
