<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Worms Invade N. Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 NAIROBI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Ghana's Ministry of Food and
Agriculture (MOFA) Monday held an emergency meeting with the
National Disaster Management Organization (NADMO) to map out
strategies to combat army worms, which have invaded farms in
northern Ghana, the Ghana News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
 The meeting, which was at the instance of Mr Johnson
Asiedu-Nketia, a Deputy Minister of Food and Agriculture, involved
the Technical Sub- committee on Pests and Insects Infestation of
NADMO.
</P>
<P>
 It reviewed strategies for eliminating or managing the menace
and addressed issues relating to the effective coordination and
dissemination of information about the invasion.
</P>
<P>
 Mr Asiedu-Nketia called for the retraining of spraying gangs
and disaster prevention volunteer corps to ensure the judicious
use of available chemicals.
</P>
<P>
 Mr Clement Bugase, another Deputy Minister of Food and
Agriculture, said spraying of affected farms has begun with the
arrival at Bolgatanga of vehicles dispatched on Saturday from
Accra with chemicals and other logistics for the exercise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990706.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Pledges to Eliminate Chemical Agents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian military Monday pledged
to eliminate chemical agents according to the related convention.
</P>
<P>
Albania is committed to implementing the convention it signed
earlier for eliminating chemical agents, said Albania's Deputy
Defense Minister Ilir Bocka here when he met with a Swiss military
expert team on chemical agents.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian Telegraphic Agence (ATA) reported that Switzerland
is undertaking a project with Albania on managing, collecting and
eliminating chemical agents, while offering technical and
financial aid to the country in this realm.
</P>
<P>
Bocka expressed thanks to Switzerland for the assistance.
</P>
<P>
Albania is a signatory to the global convention on banning the
production and use of chemical weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990706.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana's VP Meets Eritrean FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, July 5 (xINHUA) -- Ghanaian Vice-President John Evans
Atta Mills Monday met visiting Eritrean Foreign Minister Haile
Weldensai at the Castle, Osu, and reassured him of Ghana's
commitment to work for peace between his country and Ethiopia, the
Ghana News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
 "Ghana will do whatever it takes to bring peace to your two
countries",
</P>
<P>
Mills told Foreign Minister Weldensai.
</P>
<P>
 He said Ghana, as well as other well-meaning sister nations,
are " saddened by the unfortunate war that has brought unrest and
hardships to the two brothers".
</P>
<P>
 What is more worrying is that the war does not seem to be
abating despite mediation efforts from a host of countries and the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), Mills said.
</P>
<P>
 He urged the two sides to find common grounds to implement
the various pacts that were put before them. "We are mindful of
the fact that where there is war, there will be no development."
</P>
<P>
 Mills said it was time for Africa to respond to the global
trend by concentrating on development, hence the need to double
efforts to end conflicts on the continent.
</P>
<P>
 He referred to the upcoming OAU summit and said Ghana hopes
it would be used to make a strong case for peace among warring
nations so as to bring stability to the continent.
</P>
<P>
 Weldensai, who also delivered a special message from his
government to President J. Rawlings, briefed the Vice-President on
the situation and blamed Ethiopia for not being committed to the
OAU framework for peace.
</P>
<P>
 He said Eritrea was committed to peace and had made attempts
to cease- fire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
