<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Says Ready to Pass Power to New Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has
said he is ready to pass his powers over to the new leaders that
will emerge "in an honest and open election struggle" in the
future.
</P>
<P>
"We must have the elections held in a worthy way. New leaders
-- young and energetic, and with new state ideas - must emerge in
Russia after them," Yeltsin said in an interview with the
newspaper Izvestia to be published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I will pass my powers over to them with a light heart,"
Yeltsin said. His term of office expires in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"It's state affairs, not regalia that a new president will
inherit. Two elections in one year is a serious load on the
nation. Ahead of us are serious political battles, which, however,
must not hamper normal economic development," Yeltsin said,
referring to parliamentary elections next December and the
presidential race next year.
</P>
<P>
He said he has his own idea of who his successor must be but
would not disclose it so as to protect him.
</P>
<P>
"If I announce his name, he will not be able to live in peace.
He will be smothered," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
His choice may be not to his personal liking, but "personal
likes and dislikes do not count here. We shall have a new and
legally elected leader, chosen by the people," Yeltsin said. "We
shall cast our votes for someone who will propose a worthy
development program and will be able to implement it."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said he would like to see new faces in the next
parliament that should be "competent, politically responsible and
incorruptible."
</P>
<P>
"Those who have been doing big-time politics over all these
years are known too well. We need fresh forces to tackle the new
challenges of the new century," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
