<DOCNO> XIE19990706.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch, Germans Want EU Energy Tax Hike Supported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands and Germany said
Monday that raising European Union (EU) energy taxes need to have
broad support at next week's meeting of EU finance ministers.
</P>
<P>
"We share many common convictions, for example energy taxes. We
all have an interest in raising energy taxes in a smooth way,"
German Finance Minister Hans Eichel told a news briefing in The
Hague after an informal meeting with his Dutch counterpart, Gerrit
Zalm.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries are seeking a common policy within
the EU and all 15 finance ministers of the EU member states will
discuss the tax issue next week. Tax harmonization would be a
difficult task, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zalm also told reporters that an agreement by a majority of the
15 EU members would probably be the best way to make progress on
energy taxes. "We share the view that if not all 15 (EU members)
can make the same progress, then we should look at a group of less
than 15," he said.
</P>
<P>
Increased energy taxes would enable the European governments to
lower taxes in other areas, such as labor, while also being
positive for the environment, the Dutch finance minister said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to labor policy, Eichel said the Netherlands was very
successful in employing young people and women as well as in the
creation of part-time jobs, while Germany was ahead in employing
older people.
</P>
<P>
"We're interested in learning from the Netherlands... we both
can learn from each other," Eichel said, adding that given the
differences between the two countries, Germany could not simply
apply the Dutch labor model.
</P>
<P>
"The relations are different. In the Netherlands the social
partners are much closer to each other. A consensus is easier to
reach in the Netherlands than in a big country like Germany," the
German finance minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
