<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Gender Conference Opens in Accra, Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The ninth International Conference
of Gender and Science and Technology Association opened in Accra
Monday to discuss strategies of the gender factor in science, the
Ghana News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The theme of this year's meeting is "From policy to action in
gender, science and technology for sustainable development in the
21st century."
</P>
<P>
The five-day meeting, the first to be held in Africa, bring
together some 300 policy makers, administrators and teachers from
all over the world to deliberate on strategies for integrate the
gender factor into science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Chairperson of the conference, Jayshree Mehta, said that even
though science and technology has made the world a global village,
it has not been able to bridge the gap between the rich and poor
and between men and women.
</P>
<P>
She mentioned high dropout rates among girls, high illiteracy
rate and imbalance in science education for women and lack of
policy direction toward science education as some forms of the
inequality.
</P>
<P>
Mehta noted that science and technology could bridge the gap if
it is used to improve upon the lives of women and children.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian Education Minister, Ekwow Spio-Garbrah, said that men
and women should be seen as the wings on which a nation's
development flies, therefore, the inclusion of women in the
advancement of science and technology is important to development.
</P>
<P>
He said attempts have been made by his government to correct
imbalances in boy-girl education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990706.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Role of Women Cannot Be Overlooked: Rawlings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings
said in Accra Monday that the work and contribution of African
women toward sustainable development can no longer be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings made the remarks when opening the ninth International
Conference on Gender, Science and Technology, the Ghana News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that a lot have been done to ensure equal
opportunity for all to have access to science and technology,
especially with regard to education, information and employment.
</P>
<P>
For instance, he said, efforts to include women in top
management and decision-making posts have gone far to the level of
18 women parliamentarians and six female ministers.
</P>
<P>
"We are not satisfied with these figures. We shall not relent
on our efforts," Rawlings said. "Women's interest must be further
considered in national planning and budgeting."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the desire of Ghana is to achieve equity
with regards to gender in all sectors and correct the strong
cultural biases that prevent women from being involved in science
and technology.
</P>
<P>
The president urged the conference to make critical analysis of
the various policies and program toward women empowerment so that
those policies could be used for future planning.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the first to be held in Africa, is under the
theme " From policy to action in gender, science and technology
for sustainable development in the 21st century." 
</P>
</TEXT>
