<HEADLINE> Namibia Wants Troops Back From Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Any development would be
welcomed which would enable Namibia to withdraw its troops from
Congo (K) so that it could concentrate on its own problems,
Namibian Prime Minister Hage Geingob said in Durban Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Any development which will enable us to bring our soldiers
back to concentrate on alleviating poverty and to develop our
country will be most welcome," Geingob was quoted by South African
Press Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, along with Zimbabwe, has sent troops and supplies to
back Congolese President Laurent Kabila in the 11-month-old
conflict in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
On Namibia's decision to send troops, Geingob said: "Our aim
was limited. We were there for a limited purpose. We are a small
country."
</P>
<P>
Geingob stressed that Namibian President Sam Nujoma had been
engaged in peace efforts throughout and had hosted several
meetings to resolve the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he was not abreast of the latest
developments in Zambian capital Lusaka where the warring parties
are trying to thrash out a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
But he praised negotiators in Lusaka, saying that they were
working hard to ensure peace and stability in the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) region.
</P>
<P>
According to news reports from Lusaka, the long-awaited
cease-fire agreement could be signed soon.
</P>
<P>
Talks were suspended Monday to allow participants to attend the
funeral of late Zimbabwean Vice-President Joshua Nkomo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
