<HEADLINE> Kenya Gets Grant for Bomb Blast Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROB, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Red Cross has received a
one-million-U.S. dollars grant from the U.S. Agency for
International Development to increase psychological support to
victims of the Nairobi bomb blast on August 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here Monday, the Nairobi Regional
Delegation of the International Federation of Red Cross and Red
Crescent Societies announced that the grant for a two-year program
designed to deal with the consequences of the terrorist attack
will target over 6,200 families.
</P>
<P>
The program will reach out to more than 200 Kenyan families
which lost a relative in the blast, 5,000 which had someone
injured and 500 which had family members hospitalized, said the
federation.
</P>
<P>
Psychiatrist Lorin Mimless, consultant to the program, said
that "we need to help individual cope with their trauma, and also
want to increase mental health awareness generally in Kenya and
strengthen the mental health aspects of disaster preparedness."
</P>
<P>
The release said the Kenya Red Cross would establish a trauma
center with psychologists, psychiatrists and counsellors, and
provide direct services as well as outreach.
</P>
<P>
The program will also train teachers, Red Cross branch members
and community leaders in relevant areas of mental health, it
added.
</P>
<P>
Mimless held the view that the experience of helping people in
Kenya could assist other countries to deal more effectively with
trauma victims.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Agency for International Development administers the
U.S. foreign assistance program providing economic and
humanitarian assistance in more than 80 countries worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
